["Tara flour originates from seeds of the _Tara spinosa_ plant, also known as tara, Peruvian carob, or spiny holdback. This small tree is native to Peru and other parts of South America but has also "been introduced to Asia, the Middle East, and Africa. In the food industry, you can find tara in the form of flour, which is a white or beige powder that has been available in the North American market as a plant-based source of protein. Or as gum, which is used as a thickening agent, stabilizer, or gelling agent to improve the texture of food in certain products.

"According to the FDA's Department of Health and Human Services documentation, tannic acid obtained by solvent extraction of tara seed pods has been categorized as "direct food substances affirmed as generally recognized as safe." Tara seed flour is known for its high levels of protein, and some nutrients, containing about 12 grams of protein, 85 milligrams of calcium, and 729 milligrams of potassium per serving. This is, in part, why Daily Harvest looked to the ingredient when configuring a plant-based alternative meat product."
(https://www.wellandgood.com/how-to-wash-produce/)

When all is considered, I wonder if tara flour is the culprit, or what other contaminant has been ground into the flour? Perhaps a false tara plant, if there is such a thing?

Numerous other plants may be mistaken for a different plant. I wonder if the tara plant has been misidentified if indeed it is the true culprit. I don't see evidence of any genetic testing of the plant. Likely, there is some testing to ensure it is the tara flour, but I am curious if there is any other plant that could have unintentionally been harvested at the same time.

Hopefully, this will be resolved soon. - Mod.TG

Interestingly and with coincidental timing, a Revive Superfood's tara flour-containing product has also been implicated as causing illness/liver issues (https://abc7news.com/revive-superfoods-tara-flour-poisoning-mango-pineapple-smoothies-daily-harvest/12062344/). As noted in TG's comment above, tara plants contain tannic acid/tannins so one has to wonder if there are residual tannins in some batches of the flour product as acute ingestion of large amounts of tannins can cause gastrointestinal illness, abdominal pain, and liver damage (https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/tannin#:~:text=Tannic%20acid%20is%20moderately%20toxic,result%20in%20centralobular%20liver%20necrosis). - Mod.JH

This story is emerging -- it seems -- entirely from consumer reports; I have seen nothing from clinicians, the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, or state epidemiologists. ProMED would be grateful for some hard data from knowledgeable sources. - Mod.SH

